WEBVTT

00:00:00.560 --> 00:00:02.800
Next up, please welcome Becky Hodge.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:10.720
Hi everyone, I'm Becky, and today I'm going to talk about automating event scheduling,

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.040
specifically in the context of conferences. To give you some background about myself,

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:19.680
I'm a bioinformatics consultant with ProCogia, and it's my day job, but outside of that,

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.240
I also love to write. And thankfully, in Atlanta, there's a really awesome writing community here.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:30.480
So I'm part of the Atlanta Writers Club, and it's the oldest, largest, and most active organization

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:35.520
in the southeast for writers. And one of the ways in which they help writers is that twice a year,

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.639
they host a writing conference. And sort of the goal of this conference is that, you know,

00:00:40.639 --> 00:00:45.599
writers come from all over the country to attend, because they get to meet with literary agents and

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:50.639
editors who will hopefully help them get their books published. So the first time I attended

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:56.080
was in 2019 as a participant, and then I started volunteering in 2022. And then this past May for

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:01.840
the 2025 conference, I took over all the event scheduling. And sort of before I dive into that,

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:05.199
I do want to point out that, you know, there's kind of multiple kinds of conferences. And so,

00:01:05.199 --> 00:01:09.680
you know, Posit right now is more of a general conference. You know, we sign up for the entire

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:14.160
conference, and then we can kind of roam freely between all the different events. Whereas the

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:18.800
Atlanta Writers Conference, you're signing up per event, because the way it works is, you know,

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.120
you're not really there for the workshops and the mini seminars. You're there to meet with

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:27.680
the literary agents and editors for a query letter critique or a pitch or a manuscript critique.

00:01:28.559 --> 00:01:32.160
So, you know, when you go to sign up for this conference, you sign up for the particular

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:35.440
activity with the person you want to meet with, you know, because they're representing your genre.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.519
But note that we don't have you sign up for a time slot at all. And that's because, you know,

00:01:41.519 --> 00:01:45.519
we want you to be happy when you sign up and just be excited about everything and not be

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:50.239
stressing about how to schedule everything. But that obviously means that us on the back end,

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:54.720
we have to do all of that scheduling. So, you know, we have to make sure that everybody gets

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:59.040
what they signed up and paid for with zero time conflicts and that they've got plenty of time to

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:04.239
move between events without getting stressed out. So, obviously, you know, when I heard this,

00:02:04.239 --> 00:02:09.039
I was like, that's a coding problem. And I especially thought that when I discovered that

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:14.160
they were doing this manually in Excel. And there's like 300 plus people that come to this

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.479
event and you can sign up for like 15 different events. So, that was a lot. So, yeah. So, I did

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:23.279
this all in Python and Positron. The code is on GitHub if you want to check it out. But since we

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:26.160
only got five minutes, I'm not really going to talk about that. I'm just going to talk about

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:32.479
the impacts of that scheduling. So, the first big thing was that basically none of the code changes.

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:36.559
So, I set up the code so that the only thing you really change every six months is the inputs in

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:39.919
the Excel file. So, you know, the different literary agents and editors that are coming

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:43.919
and the different workshop talks and stuff like that. But otherwise, the code remains the same.

00:02:45.039 --> 00:02:48.639
The second big thing is that they also used to send out individual emails with people's

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:54.880
schedules attached. I fixed that as well. So, you know, now basically the code populates the

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:00.800
custom fields that go into Miller Lite and we can with a few clicks send out a single bulk email

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:05.279
with everybody's personalized schedules prior to the event. And then the other big thing that

00:03:05.279 --> 00:03:09.520
really helped was like on like at the time of the conference stuff was the code automatically

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:14.000
outputs, you know, everybody's individual schedules, their name tags, you know, the conference rosters,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.880
all that sort of stuff. So, they can just print it out and we're sort of ready to go for the

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:22.160
conference. So, these three things really helped make the conference remain a really big success

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:27.039
but with a lot less effort. So, that was really nice. And by far the biggest impact is that, you

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:32.160
know, went from spending like 200 plus hours every six months on this to, you know, maybe spending

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:37.360
like 20 hours. And that's awesome because the next one's in October and I will be doing that.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:42.000
And so, I'm very excited to only spend maybe like a weekend on this instead of an entire month.

00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:52.080
So, thank you. That was my talk.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:02.660
Thank you.

